1 Introduction - What is Shiny?

Shiny is an R package that allows the user to create interactive web apps. Just like other popular R packages, including the tidyverse packages, it was created by members of the RStudio team and was first released as version 0.2.3 on December 1st 2012. The most current version is 1.6.0 and was released on January 25th 2021. Further information on the current and past versions can be found here.

Before the package was released, it was more difficult for R users to create web apps. Either there was the possibility to work with the tcltk package, which was announced in 2001 and is also a graphic user interface (GUI) but with different shortcomings, or it required knowledge of HTML, CSS and JavaScript. Furthermore, this required the user to carefully analyze the interaction flows and dependencies of their code to prevent unrelated outputs to change, when some input changes. Shiny solves those problems by providing user interface (UI) functions that generate the needed HTML, CSS and JavaScript, which means that the user doesnt have to have any knowledge on these, if they dont want to go beyond the provided basics. It also introduced a new style of programming. Reactive programming keeps track of the dependencies in the code, which enables Shiny to be able to automatically figure out, how to do most efficiently update the output, if the input changes (Wickham 2021).

Shiny is used to create dashboards that replace hundreds of PDFs by allowing the user to immediately jump to the slice of data they are interested in and make it easy to communicate complex models to a nontechnical audience and visualize the data accordingly (2021). Shiny can also be used to create interactive documents such as this one, by adding runtime: shiny in the documents YAML header.

In the first section the structure and functions of shiny apps will be explained. After that, some examples of shiny apps and their respective codes will be presented.

2 Structure of a Shiny app

In this section we will show the structure behind apps that are created with Shiny. Before users can start to work with Shiny, they have to install and load the package.

# Installing Shiny
if (!require("shiny")) install.packages("shiny")

# Loading Shiny
library(shiny)

A Shiny app essentially consists of two components, each of which can be implemented as a function in R. The first one being the UI function containing everything in terms of app layout, themes and control elements. This part of the app will be covered in section 2.1. The second part of a Shiny app consists of yet another function, the so called server function. All server-side tasks are carried out here. This includes, for example, generating outputs and handling user inputs. Section 2.2 deals with this part of the app. The code of these two components can be placed inside a single file, app.R. This file must return an object created by theshinyApp() function. However, for larger applications an individual ui.R and server.R file can be used, to give the code base a cleaner structure. The following example shows the code layout and function calls for a standalone Shiny app implemented in a single app.R file.

# Define UI for application. 
# Here, a fluid Page layout is used.
ui <- fluidPage(
  # code for ui layout
)

# Define server logic as function of inputs and outputs.
server <- function(input, output) {
  # code for server logic
}

# Run the shiny application.
shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

2.1 Adding controls - UI

There are three groups of functions that can be used to design the user interface of a Shiny app. The first group of functions are the UI layout functions which are used for laying out the user interface for the application. Users can decide if they want a page with a fixed layout using fixedPage or a fluid layout using fluidPage, create icons using icon or create a panel containing an application title using titlePanel for example.

The second group of functions are the UI input functions. These functions are used to create user interface elements that prompt the user for input values or interaction, such as checkboxes, sliders or drop-down menus for example.

This allows us to pass on values for variables directly from the user to the server logic. To fulfill this purpose, all input functions have the same first argument inputId which is an unique identifier string for the input value. If one creates an input function with inputId = my_control, this can be accessed in the server function with input$my_control. Looking at the slider example form above, the code of choosing a value between \(0\) and \(2\), labeled with slider is given below.

sliderInput(inputId = "my_slider", label = "slider",
              min = 0, max = 2, value = 1, step = 0.1)

The last group of functions are the UI output functions. They create user interface elements that, in conjunction with server side rendering function, display different kinds of output from the application, like text, plots or tables. They are used in a similar manner to the input functions. Each output function therefore has the same first argument outputId, again representing an unique identifier string. These identifiers are then used in the server function like output$my_output paired with a render() function to process and display the output. The code below gives an example of how to integrate text, a plot and a table in the layout of the shiny app.

textOutput(outputId = "my_text")
plotOutput(outputId = "my_plot")
tableOutput(outputId = "my_table")

The following section will give a brief overview of combining the UI elements from this section with more logic and interacting with the variable values.

2.2 Adding behavior - server

The server function brings the output of the app to life by telling Shiny how to perform computations, for example how to fill a plot or a table with data. The full documentation of all the functions can be found here. We will use the input and output arguments of our server() function to pass the elements of our ui object to each other. First consider the slider example from the previous section. Lets say, one would like to display the chosen number as a simple text object in the app. We can achieve it by using the following code. In the server function we add the output$my_text object, which is linked to the UI component via the unique identifier string my_text as a member of the output argument. Furthermore we use the renderText() function, since we want to display plain text. Here input$my_slider is used to fetch the number on the slider from the user input.

# Define UI for application. 
ui <- fluidPage(
  # Slider function.
  sliderInput(inputId = "my_slider", label = "slider",
              min = 0, max = 2, value = 1, step = 0.1),
  
  # Text output function.
  textOutput(outputId = "my_text")
)

# Define server logic as function of inputs and outputs.
server <- function(input, output) {
  output$my_text <- renderText({ 
    paste0("Your number is: ", input$my_slider)
  })
}

# Run the shiny application.
shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

Extra: Using Shiny in documents - interactive documents

There are two ways to include interactive Shiny elements in a document. You can either directly add widgets and rendered output in the document or you can embed a standalone Shiny app within the document (Grolemund 2014; Xie, Allaire, and Grolemund 2019).

2.3 Deploying the app

After one has completed the work on an app, the question of how the software can go into production in order to reach the users must be answered. Shiny and RStudio are therefore offering a few solutions. The simplest way of running an R Shiny app is by doing it locally on your own computer. Here, an R and Shiny installation are required. A more common solution is to deploy the Shiny app to the web. The advantages of this option are that one can reach a larger target group and that end users only need a web browser to run the app. Rolling out on a server can be done using the ShinyServer software from RStudio. A Linux server or cloud-based Linux server is required for this. A simpler solution can be achieved via Shinyapps.io, a cloud hosting services by RStudio. This has the advantage that the developer doesnt need to take care of the hardware and the installation of the server. Only the app code needs to be transferred to the Shinyapps.io service. There are different price models for this deploying method - including a free solution. More on this topic can be found here.

3 Examples

In this section we will present some examples of shiny apps, which were written by us. The first example will be a distribution plotter to show that shiny apps can be written in just a few lines of code. The second example is an interactive regression to show the statistical capabilities of shiny. The final app is a Covid-19 dashboard to show how shiny can be used to make data accessible to people without a programming or statistical background.

3.1 Distribution plotter

As stated above the first example is a distribution plotter. It is an application which can draw the density functions of different distributions. The chosen distributions for the application are beta distribution, normal distribution and \(t\)-distribution.

library(shiny)

# Define UI for application that draws different distributions
ui <- fluidPage(
    
    # Application title
    titlePanel("Distribution plotter"),

After installing and loading the shiny package the UI has to be defined. This includes the layout and the interactive elements. In this case a dropdown menu and sliders. The function fluidPage() is used to create a fluid layout which means that the layout is composed of rows and columns to keep all content in line. A Fluid page layout is not fixed but scales its components depending on the window size. After determining which layout should be used, the layout can be set.

# Sidebar with different distr. / params 
sidebarLayout(
    sidebarPanel(
        selectInput("distr",
                    label = "Which distribution?",
                    choices = c("Beta", "Normal", "t"), selected="Beta"),

sidebarLayout() defines that on the left side a sidebar can be created using the function sidebarPanel() and on the right side the main area which includes the visualization using the function mainPanel(). The sidebar includes a dropdown menu which is created with selectInput(). In this menu a distribution can be selected - normal, beta or t. Furthermore, the sidebar includes sliders where the values of the parameters can be chosen.

conditionalPanel(
    condition = "input.distr == 'Beta'",
    sliderInput(
        "alpha",
        "Value of Alpha",
        1,
        10,
        1,
        step = 1)
),
conditionalPanel(
    condition = "input.distr == 'Beta'",
    sliderInput(
        "beta",
        "Value of Beta",
        1,
        10,
        1,
        step = 1)
),
conditionalPanel(
    condition = "input.distr == 'Normal'",
    sliderInput(
        "mu",
        "Value of Mu",
        -10,
        10,
        0,
        step = 1)
),
conditionalPanel(
    condition = "input.distr == 'Normal'",
    sliderInput(
        "sigma",
        "Value of Sigma",
        1,
        10,
        1,
        step = 1)
),
conditionalPanel(
    condition = "input.distr == 't'",
    sliderInput(
        "t_DF",
        "Degrees of freedom",
        1,
        10,
        1,
        step = 1)
)

The sliders are created with the function conditionalPanel(). Depending on which distribution was chosen in the dropdown menu above, the parameters and their value range vary.

For the beta-distribution which is defined as follows:

\[\begin{align*} & X \sim {\sf Beta}(\alpha, \beta) \\ & p(x|\alpha, \beta) = \frac{\Gamma(\alpha + \beta)}{\Gamma(\alpha)\Gamma(\beta)}x^{\alpha -1}(1-x)^{\beta -1} \: \text{for} \: 0 < x < 1 \\ & \text{with} \: \alpha,\beta > 0 \end{align*}\]

the parameters are \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\). For the sliders we chose a value range between \(1\) and \(10\) for each parameter.

For the normal distribution

\[\begin{align*} & X \sim \mathcal{N}\left( \mu, \sigma^2 \right) \\ & p(x|\mu, \sigma^2) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^2}}exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2\sigma^2}(x-\mu)^2\right\} \: \text{for} \: x \in R \\ & \text{with} \: \mu \in \mathbb{R} \: \text{and} \: \sigma^2 > 0 \end{align*}\]

the value of \(\mu\) was chosen to be in the range between \(-10\) and \(10\) and the value of \(\sigma\) in the range of \(1\) to \(10\).

The \(t\)-distribution depends on the degrees of freedom \(\nu\).

\[\begin{align*} & X \sim t_{\nu} \\ & p(x|\nu) = \frac{\Gamma \left( \frac{\nu + 1}{2} \right)}{\sqrt{\nu\pi}\Gamma \left( \frac{\nu}{2} \right)} \left( 1+\frac{x^2}{\nu} \right)^{-\frac{\nu+1}{2}} \: \text{for} \: x \in \mathbb{R} \\ & \text{with} \: \nu \in \mathbb{N} \end{align*}\]

For the \(t\)-distribution the degrees of freedom can be choosen from \(1\) to \(10\). After creating the sidebar, the main panel has to be defined.

# Show a plot of the generated distribution
mainPanel(
    plotOutput("plot")
)

With the function mainPanel(plotOutput(plot)) a plot is created next to the sidebar. The plot varies depending on the chosen distribution. Now that the UI is defined, the server logic has to be set.

# Define server logic required to draw distribution plots
server <- function(input, output) {
    pbeta <- seq(0,1,0.01)
    pnormal <- seq(-10, 10, 0.01)
    pt <- seq(-10, 10, 0.01)
    output$plot <- renderPlot({
        if (input$distr == "Beta"){
            plot(pbeta, dbeta(pbeta, input$alpha, input$beta), 
                 type="l", 
                 ylab="Density",
                 xlab ="X",
                 col = 4)
        } else if (input$distr == "Normal"){
            plot(pnormal, dnorm(pnormal, input$mu, input$sigma), 
                 type="l",
                 ylab="Density",
                 xlab ="X",
                 col = 3)
        } else if (input$distr == "t"){
            plot(pt, dt(pt, input$t_DF), 
                 type = "l",
                 ylab="Density",
                 xlab ="X",
                 col = 2)
        }
    })
}

# Run the application 
shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

The server logic is required to draw the distribution plots which are shown in the main panel. The plots are generated depending on the input given via the dropdown menu selection and the slider selection. The reactive plots are rendered using rendersPlot(). Via an if condition the selection of the distribution in the dropdown menu is considered. Depending on the selected distribution the different plots are created by determining the range of the x axis and the type of distribution and considering the selected values for the parameters. Furthermore, the color of the graphs and the type of plot are set as well as the description of the \(y\)- and \(x\)-axis. Now the UI and also the server logic are defined which means that the app can run. The app can be seen below.

3.2 Interactive Regression

The application presented in this section is intended to clarify the interactive components in relation to statistical data analysis. The following app can calculate two linear models of the form

\[\begin{align*} y = \textbf{X}\beta + \epsilon \end{align*}\]

for one data set simultaneously. The results can be compared directly. Therefore the Akaike information criterion (AIC) is calculated for each of the two models. The model specification can be changed at any time. So the AIC is an indicator, if the new specification yields a better model. Here, the model with the lowest AIC value is considered to be the best model. Another interesting view on model selection is provided by the plot in the app. This more machine-learning-like approach takes a partition of the data set, also called a test set, to calculate predictions with the fitted models. These predictions can be compared to the true test values. The train/test split rate can also be controlled in the app. This gives us some insight on how good we can make true predictions of each of the two models. Note that the models are fitted (trained) with the other partition of the initial data set, the so called training data set. In the following part of this section we will present the code and the app itself.

First, we need to include the packages for our interactive regression app. As an example data set we use the BostonHousing data set from the mlbench package.

# Include shiny.
if (!require("shiny")) install.packages("shiny")
library(shiny)

# Install the package containing the data.
if (!require("mlbench")) install.packages("mlbench")
library(mlbench)

The BostonHousing data set contains 506 census tracts of Boston from the 1970 census on 14 variables. The target being medv which represents the median value of owner-occupied homes in USD 1000s.

The rest of these variables should be interactively used to change our model specifications. Therefore we save the names of these variables in a vector. Also the target is saved in an R variable. We are using length(colnames(BostonHousing)) for implicit indexing.

target <- colnames(BostonHousing)[length(colnames(BostonHousing))]
variables <- colnames(BostonHousing)[1:(length(colnames(BostonHousing)) - 1)]

In the next step we implement a wrapper function fitLinearModel() for the lm() function of R. The latter function is part of the R stats package and is used to fit linear models of the above form. The wrapper takes a target input argument, which represents the target variable of the linear model. The variables argument is used to pass the variables for the fit of the linear model. Furthermore, the full data set dataset and the percentage value splitRate of training data, split from the full set, is passed to the wrapper function. With the first two arguments we can dynamically build the formula object for the lm() function. Here, a for loop is used to put together the object. In the next block, the train/test split is performed. A seed is used to ensure reproducible results. With that together, we can now fit the model using the training data. After that we use AIC() to calculate the value of the Akaike information criterion. Predictions are then calculated via predict(), now using the test data. Lastly, the absolute error is calculated as the difference between the true values and the predicted values. All of the results are merged into a single list() return object for further use.

fitLinearModel <- function(target, variables, dataset, splitRate){
  # Fits a linear model for the provided target and
  # variables of the passed data set. 
  modelFormula <- paste0(target, " ~")
  counter <- 0
  
  # Set up formula object for the linear model.
  for (variable in variables){
    if (counter == 0){
      modelFormula <- paste0(modelFormula, " ", variable)
    } else {
      modelFormula <- paste0(modelFormula, " + ", variable)
    }
    counter <- counter + 1
  }
  
  # Perform train/test split of the provided data set.
  set.seed(420)
  sampleSize <- floor(splitRate * nrow(dataset))
  trainIdx <- sample(seq_len(nrow(dataset)), size = sampleSize)
  trainData <- dataset[trainIdx, ]
  testData <- dataset[-trainIdx, ]
  
  # Fit the linear model and calculate predictions.
  modelFit <- lm(formula = modelFormula, data = trainData)
  modelAIC <- AIC(modelFit)
  modelPredictions <- predict(modelFit, newdata = testData)
  modelPredictionError <- abs(modelPredictions - testData[target])
  
  result <- list(model = modelFit, 
                 AIC = modelAIC, 
                 predictions = modelPredictions, 
                 predictionErrors = modelPredictionError,
                 trueValues = testData[target])
  
  return(result)
}

This is all of the pre processing needed for the app. We can now start to write the code for the shiny app. As always, we begin with the UI component of the app. For this app, we use the fluidPage() layout. Some standard HTML h1(), p() tags are used to provied some information for the user as simple text on the page. After that, we add a slider to control the train/test split rate by using sliderInput(). Since we want to control two models and their variables simultaneously, we split the fluidPage() into two equally sized columns using column(). Each of the two columns contains a checkboxGroupInput() and a textOutput(). The first one being a list of selectable items representing our model variables. The latter is an interface for the text output, which will display the AIC value of the model. Finally a plot output placeholder is added by plotOutput().

ui <- fluidPage(
  
  h1("Interactive Linear Regression Models"),
  
  p("Use the checkboxes below to specifiy the variables for each of the two 
    linear models. At least one variable must be selected for each model.
    The train/test split rate can be controlled by the silder."),
  
  sliderInput("splitRate", "Select the percentage of training data (both models)", 
              min = 0.1, max = 0.95, step = 0.05, value = 0.85),
  
  fluidRow(
    column(6,
           checkboxGroupInput("variablesModel1", "Choose variables for model 1:",
                              selected = variables[1],
                              choiceNames =
                                variables,
                              choiceValues =
                                variables
           ),
           
           textOutput("modelAIC_1")
    ),
    
    column(6,
           checkboxGroupInput("variablesModel2", "Choose variables for model 2:",
                              selected = variables[2],
                              choiceNames =
                                variables,
                              choiceValues =
                                variables
           ),
           
           textOutput("modelAIC_2")
    )
  ),
  
  plotOutput("plotPredictions")
)

Again, the final component is the server function to define the logic of the app. We start by rendering the text output for the AIC values. We use output$modelAIC_1 <- renderText() to wrap the calculation of the linear model. Inside this function the AIC result of the fit object is fetched for the text output. The same procedure can be applied for model two, but now using the input objects for the selection of model two. Finally, the plot is rendered using output$plotPredictions <- renderPlot(). Here, both models are fitted and the return objects for setting up the plots are fetched. The data is plotted as points. To give some more context, spline interpolation is used to fit smooth curves through these points. Therefore the spline() function is used.

server <- function(input, output, session) {
  # AIC output for model 1.
  output$modelAIC_1 <- renderText({
    # Fit model
    target <- colnames(BostonHousing)[length(colnames(BostonHousing))]
    variables1 <- input$variablesModel1
    fit1 <- fitLinearModel(target, variables1, BostonHousing, input$splitRate)
    
    print(paste0("AIC of model 1: ", fit1[[2]]))
  })
  
  # AIC output for model 2.
  output$modelAIC_2 <- renderText({
    # Fit model
    target <- colnames(BostonHousing)[length(colnames(BostonHousing))]
    variables2 <- input$variablesModel2
    fit2 <- fitLinearModel(target, variables2, BostonHousing, input$splitRate)
    
    print(paste0("AIC of model 2: ", fit2[[2]]))
  })
  
  # Plot output for both models.
  output$plotPredictions <- renderPlot({
    # Fit models
    target <- colnames(BostonHousing)[length(colnames(BostonHousing))]
    variables1 <- input$variablesModel1
    fit1 <- fitLinearModel(target, variables1, BostonHousing, input$splitRate)
    
    variables2 <- input$variablesModel2
    fit2 <- fitLinearModel(target, variables2, BostonHousing, input$splitRate)
    
    # Set up plot.
    plot(c(1:length(fit1[[5]][, 1])), fit1[[5]][, 1], 
         col = "blue", pch = 1, xlab = "Index", ylab = "Target", 
         main = "Comparison of predicted test values and true values")
    lines(spline(c(1:length(fit1[[5]][, 1])), fit1[[5]][, 1]), 
          col = "blue")
    points(c(1:length(fit1[[3]])), fit1[[3]], 
           col = "red", pch = 2)
    lines(spline(c(1:length(fit1[[3]])), fit1[[3]]), 
          col = "red")
    points(c(1:length(fit2[[3]])), fit2[[3]], 
           col = "green", pch = 3)
    lines(spline(c(1:length(fit2[[3]])), fit2[[3]]), 
          col = "green")
    legend(0, 50, legend = c("True values", "model 1", "model 2"), col = c("blue", "red", "green"), lty = 1)
  })
}

3.3 Covid-19 Dashboard

This application will be the most elaborate example. We wanted to create a dashboard that shows some relevant Covid-19 data, as its still a relevant topic. We decided to include a map, which shows key data for each county, an interactive data table for users to explore the data and some plots about some more key data.

Firstly, the required packages have to be installed and loaded.

packages <- c("DT", "htmltools", "leaflet", "RColorBrewer", "sf", "shiny",
              "shinythemes", "tidyverse")

for (i in packages) { #Installs packages if not yet installed
    if(! i %in% row.names(installed.packages())) install.packages(i)
}

library(DT)
library(htmltools)
library(leaflet)
library(RColorBrewer)
library(sf)
library(shiny)
library(shinythemes)
library(tidyverse)

The packages vector contains all packages that are used in this app. DT is a package which provides an R interface to the DataTables library, which is written in Javascript. It allows R data objects to be displayed as HTML-tables. htmltools is used to generate custom HTML using R code, which can be used to customize user interfaces. leaflet integrates the equally named JavaScript library in R. It can be used to create interactive maps and customize them. RColorBrewer contains the color palettes which are used in various plots and outputs. The simple features or sf is used to read spatial data like GIS or GeoJSON. Shiny and shinythemes create the graphical user interface and its design, while the tidyverse packages are used for data wrangling and plotting (ggplot2).

After preparing the necessary packages we have to load our data into R. The RKI Corona Landkreise from the Robert-Koch-Institute was used, because it contains all the key data for each county in Germany.

load_geodata <- function(geodata_url, save_flag=FALSE) {
  # Try to read geo data from the provided URL.
  # If reading fails, an older local copy is used.
  # Set save_flag = TRUE to replace the local copy
  # with newer data.
  tryCatch(
    expr = {
      geodata <<- read_sf(geodata_url)
    }, 
    error = function(e) {
      print(paste0("Error: Failed to read data from online source: ", geodata_url))
      print("Using local data set instead.")
      save_flag <<- FALSE
      load("geodata.RData")
      geodata <<- geodata
    },
    warning = function(w) {
      print(paste0("Warning: Failed to parse data from JSON source: ", geodata_url))
      print("Using local data set instead.")
      save_flag <<- FALSE
      load("geodata.RData")
      geodata <<- geodata
    }
  )
  
  if (save_flag) {
    # Saving data object in RData format.
    save(geodata, file = "geodata.RData")
  }
}


# Get geo data from online source.
geodata_url <- "https://opendata.arcgis.com/datasets/917fc37a709542548cc3be077a786c17_0.geojson"
load_geodata(geodata_url, save_flag = FALSE)

The data is provided as GeoJSON file and can be accessed by using an API link provided on the website. The load_geodata() acts as an error handler. After running the code for the first time the data will be saved as RData object, which can be used as substitute data in case the API cant be reached. As the data is provided as GeoJSON file, the easiest way to read the data into R is by using the read_sf() function from the sf package.

navbarPage() creates a layout with a navigation bar on the top of the dashboard. The shinytheme flatly is used, which changes the visuals of the UI. The title is set by the string Covid-19 in Germany. After creating the navbar layout, the function tabPanel() is used to create tabs within the layout. This app contains three tabs. The first tab is labeled Map and contains the interactive leaflet map. fillPage() creates a window that will always fill the browser window. The map object is labeled c19map and a height of 1000 pixels is set. It is rendered by the leafletOutput() function. The second tab contains the datatable. The second row contains the different plots in three columns. The columns are 4 units wide each, which make them take up the whole horizontal space (12 units). output$piechart <- renderPlot({
    #piechart
    if (input$region == "Germany (total)"){
      gdata %>% 
        mutate(sumcases = sum(cases)) %>% 
        mutate(BL = fct_lump_n(BL, n=5, w=sumcases)) %>% 
        group_by(BL) %>%
        summarise(cases_sum = sum(cases)) %>% 
        mutate(percentage = round(cases_sum/sum(cases_sum)*100, digits = 2)) %>% 
        ggplot(., aes(x="", y=percentage, fill=BL)) + 
        geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
        coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
        theme_void() + 
        theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.direction = "horizontal") +
        scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Pastel2") +
        geom_text(aes(label=paste0(percentage, "%"), x=1.3), 
                  position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size=3) + 
        labs(title = "Percentage of the states in total number of cases",
             subtitle = "Top 5 and rest",
             fill = "")
      
    } else {
      
      bundesland <- input$region
      
      if (input$region == bundesland){
        gdata %>% mutate(BL = as.factor(ifelse(BL==bundesland, bundesland, "other"))) %>% 
          group_by(BL) %>%
          summarise(cases_sum = sum(cases)) %>% 
          mutate(percentage = round(cases_sum/sum(cases_sum)*100, digits = 2)) %>%
          ggplot(., aes(x="", y=percentage, fill=reorder(BL, percentage))) + 
          geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
          coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
          theme_void() + 
          theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.direction = "horizontal") +
          scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Pastel2") +
          geom_text(aes(label=paste0(percentage, "%"), x=1.3), 
                    position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size=3) + 
          labs(title = paste("Percentage of", bundesland, "in total number of cases"),
               subtitle = "compared to all other states",
               fill = "")
      }
    }
  })

The first plot on the page is a pie chart, showing either the percentages of the top 5 states in total number of cases in Germany or the percentage of a state in total number of cases compared to Germany as a whole. What is shown is decided by the dropdown menu input on the page. If Germany (total) is chosen, the top 5 states will be displayed. It is created by the renderPlot() function. For that, the data of the states outside the top 5 had to be grouped. This is done by the fct_lump_n() command. Next the data was grouped, summarized and a percentage variable was created. A pie chart cant be created directly using ggplot2. It can however be created by defining a bar plot using geom_bar() and making the bar plot object circular using coord_polar(). The theme was set to void using theme_void() because it keeps the background of the plot white and removes the axis. The palette was set in scale_fill_brewer(), while the percentage numbers and labels were created by geom_text() and labs() respectively. If a specific state is chosen in the dropdown menu, the data manipulation varies a bit compared to the manipulation of the data for Germany as a whole. The manipulation is specific to each state and is changed via if condition. After that the variable BL containing all the states is changed to a factor variable, where the chosen state is the first and other is the second factor. The rest of the code (i.e., the ggplot2 code for the pie chart) is equal to the one explained above.

The remaining plots were all created equally with just the data manipulation and some text differing between them. Because of that only one of the remaining plots will be explained in full length.

output$c7_hi <- renderPlot({
    #plot of LKs with highest c7/100k

             x="County",

      if (input$region == bundesland){
        
        xLabs <- gdata %>%

        gdata %>% 
          filter(BL == bundesland) %>%

               subtitle = "Counties with the highest 7-day-incidence",

      }

The plot explained can be seen in the middle of the upper row in the Plots-tab. It shows the counties with the highest amount of cases per 100.000 inhabitants in the last 7 days. If the dropdown menu item Germany (total) is selected the counties with the top 5 highest values of entire Germany will be displayed, if a state is chosen the counties with the top 5 values within the state are displayed. The plot is again created by the renderPlot() function. Firstly, a character vector xLabs is created for the labels. Why this is needed will be explained a little later. Then the data is arranged in descending order of cases per 100.000 in the last 7 days and the top 5 counties are chosen. Then a bar plot is created using geom_col(). Because some cities are counties and have the same name as the county surrounding them (i.e., Bamberg city and Bamberg county) the type of county (city/not city/etc.) and the name of the county were pasted together to prevent inconsistent plotting and stacking of the data. This is why the xLabs object had to be created. It is used for the x-axis text and makes it easier to read by reversing the combination of both strings. The data was also ordered from highest to lowest inside of the plot using reorder(). The scale_fill_distiller() function was used to color the plot and scale the color with the value. The theme classic was set using theme_classic() and was chosen for aesthetic reasons. The x-axis text was rotated 90 degrees and a line break function for better readability using angle inside the theme() function and str_wrap() inside the scale_x_discrete() function. The legend and title were added in the labs() function. If a state is selected the creation of the plot is done equally except the data manipulation. Here the data is first filtered by the selected state using an if condition and filter(). The rest of the code remains the same except some strings for the legend.

As stated above, the other plots were all created in the same way except using other arrange() or filter() functions and different labels. The code for the other plots can be found in the source code of our GitHub-repository or in the appendix at the end.

4 Conclusion

Nowadays there is a need for clear visualization and interactions with large amounts of data in almost every area. Dashboards that use simple controls to set filters or restrict the display to a specific area of interest are particularly popular. With this solution, a wide range of users can be offered an intuitive presentation of the facts. In addition to the already mentioned purpose for the end user, the possibilities of creating such a tool in the programming language R presented in this paper offer further advantages. The R shiny package provides the developer a simple interface to create a link between to the classic statistical work and the summarizing of the results in a dashboard or a web app. The user interface and the server logic behind it can be implemented with a few functions. This can be done entirely within R, so no further knowledge of other web technologies is required. The examples in this document show how versatile R Shiny apps and dashboards can be. In addition to the usual control elements known from websites and computer programs, tables and plots can also be inserted. Even the integration of interactive maps can be done relatively easily. In the age of the web, R Shiny solutions represent an easily configurable and fast solution for preparing the core content of a topic for various target groups.

# Define server logic required to draw distribution plots
server <- function(input, output) {
    pbeta <- seq(0,1,0.01)
    pnormal <- seq(-10, 10, 0.01)
    pt <- seq(-10, 10, 0.01)
    output$plot <- renderPlot({
        if (input$distr == "Beta"){
            plot(pbeta, dbeta(pbeta, input$alpha, input$beta), 
                 type="l", 
                 ylab="Density",
                 xlab ="X",
                 col = 4)
        } else if (input$distr == "Normal"){
            plot(pnormal, dnorm(pnormal, input$mu, input$sigma), 
                 type="l",
                 ylab="Density",
                 xlab ="X",
                 col = 3)
        } else if (input$distr == "t"){
            plot(pt, dt(pt, input$t_DF), 
                 type = "l",
                 ylab="Density",
                 xlab ="X",
                 col = 2)
        }
    })
}

# Run the application 
shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

5.2 Code of interactive regression

# regression_app.R
# In this script the Boston housing data set is used
# to predict the house price in Boston from house
# details. This is the foundation of an interactive
# shiny dashboard where you can compare two types 
# of linear models. A discription of the data can be
# found here:
# https://www.rdocumentation.org/packages/mlbench/versions/2.1-3/topics/BostonHousing


# Include shiny.
if (!require("shiny")) install.packages("shiny")
library(shiny)

# Install the package containing the data.
if (!require("mlbench")) install.packages("mlbench")


fitLinearModel <- function(target, variables, dataset, splitRate){
  # Fits a linear model for the provided target and
  # variables of the passed data set. 
  modelFormula <- paste0(target, " ~")
  counter <- 0
  
  # Set up formula object for the linear model.
  for (variable in variables){
    if (counter == 0){
      modelFormula <- paste0(modelFormula, " ", variable)
    } else {
      modelFormula <- paste0(modelFormula, " + ", variable)
    }
    counter <- counter + 1
  }
  
  # Perform train/test split of the provided data set.
  set.seed(420)
  sampleSize <- floor(splitRate * nrow(dataset))
  trainIdx <- sample(seq_len(nrow(dataset)), size = sampleSize)
  trainData <- dataset[trainIdx, ]
  testData <- dataset[-trainIdx, ]
  
  # Fit the linear model and calculate predictions.
  modelFit <- lm(formula = modelFormula, data = trainData)
  modelAIC <- AIC(modelFit)
  modelPredictions <- predict(modelFit, newdata = testData)
  modelPredictionError <- abs(modelPredictions - testData[target])
  
  result <- list(model = modelFit, 
                 AIC = modelAIC, 
                 predictions = modelPredictions, 
                 predictionErrors = modelPredictionError,
                 trueValues = testData[target])
  
  return(result)
}


### Shiny app ###
### --------- ###

# Load the data set.
library(mlbench)
data(BostonHousing)

# Global scope
target <- colnames(BostonHousing)[length(colnames(BostonHousing))]
variables <- colnames(BostonHousing)[1:(length(colnames(BostonHousing)) - 1)]


ui <- fluidPage(
  
  h1("Interactive Linear Regression Models"),
  
  p("Use the checkboxes below to specifiy the variables for each of the two 
    linear models. At least one variable must be selected for each model.
    The train/test split rate can be controlled by the silder."),
  
  sliderInput("splitRate", "Select the percentage of training data (both models)", 
              min = 0.1, max = 0.95, step = 0.05, value = 0.85),
  
  fluidRow(
    column(6,
           checkboxGroupInput("variablesModel1", "Choose variables for model 1:",
                              selected = variables[1],
                              choiceNames =
                                variables,
                              choiceValues =
                                variables
           ),
           
           textOutput("modelAIC_1")
    ),
    
    column(6,
           checkboxGroupInput("variablesModel2", "Choose variables for model 2:",
                              selected = variables[2],
                              choiceNames =
                                variables,
                              choiceValues =
                                variables
           ),
           
           textOutput("modelAIC_2")
    )
  ),
  
  plotOutput("plotPredictions")
)

server <- function(input, output, session) {
  output$modelAIC_1 <- renderText({
    # Fit model
    target <- colnames(BostonHousing)[length(colnames(BostonHousing))]
    variables1 <- input$variablesModel1
    fit1 <- fitLinearModel(target, variables1, BostonHousing, input$splitRate)
    
    print(paste0("AIC of model 1: ", fit1[[2]]))
  })
  
  output$modelAIC_2 <- renderText({
    # Fit model
    target <- colnames(BostonHousing)[length(colnames(BostonHousing))]
    variables2 <- input$variablesModel2
    fit2 <- fitLinearModel(target, variables2, BostonHousing, input$splitRate)
    
    print(paste0("AIC of model 2: ", fit2[[2]]))
  })
  
  output$plotPredictions <- renderPlot({
    # Fit models
    target <- colnames(BostonHousing)[length(colnames(BostonHousing))]
    variables1 <- input$variablesModel1
    fit1 <- fitLinearModel(target, variables1, BostonHousing, input$splitRate)
    
    variables2 <- input$variablesModel2
    fit2 <- fitLinearModel(target, variables2, BostonHousing, input$splitRate)
    
    # Set up plot.
    plot(c(1:length(fit1[[5]][, 1])), fit1[[5]][, 1], 
         col = "blue", pch = 1, xlab = "Index", ylab = "Target", 
         main = "Comparison of predicted test values and true values")
    lines(spline(c(1:length(fit1[[5]][, 1])), fit1[[5]][, 1]), 
          col = "blue")
    points(c(1:length(fit1[[3]])), fit1[[3]], 
           col = "red", pch = 2)
    lines(spline(c(1:length(fit1[[3]])), fit1[[3]]), 
          col = "red")
    points(c(1:length(fit2[[3]])), fit2[[3]], 
           col = "green", pch = 3)
    lines(spline(c(1:length(fit2[[3]])), fit2[[3]]), 
          col = "green")
    legend(0, 50, legend = c("True values", "model 1", "model 2"), col = c("blue", "red", "green"), lty = 1)
  })
}

shinyApp(ui, server)

load_geodata <- function(geodata_url, save_flag=FALSE) {
  # Try to read geo data from the provided URL.
  # If reading fails, an older local copy is used.
  # Set save_flag = TRUE to replace the local copy
  # with newer data.
  tryCatch(
    expr = {
      geodata <<- read_sf(geodata_url)
    }, 
    error = function(e) {
      print(paste0("Error: Failed to read data from online source: ", geodata_url))
      print("Using local data set instead.")
      save_flag <<- FALSE
      load("geodata.RData")
      geodata <<- geodata
    },
    warning = function(w) {
      print(paste0("Warning: Failed to parse data from JSON source: ", geodata_url))
      print("Using local data set instead.")
      save_flag <<- FALSE
      load("geodata.RData")
      geodata <<- geodata
    }
  )
  
  if (save_flag) {
    # Saving data object in RData format.
    save(geodata, file = "geodata.RData")
  }
}

    #piechart
    if (input$region == "Germany (total)"){
      gdata %>% 
        mutate(sumcases = sum(cases)) %>%

        group_by(BL) %>%
        summarise(cases_sum = sum(cases)) %>% 
        mutate(percentage = round(cases_sum/sum(cases_sum)*100, digits = 2)) %>% 
        ggplot(., aes(x="", y=percentage, fill=BL)) + 
        geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
        coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
        theme_void() + 
        theme(legend.position = "bottom", legend.direction = "horizontal") +
        scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Pastel2") +
        geom_text(aes(label=paste0(percentage, "%"), x=1.3), 
                  position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5), size=3) +

             subtitle = "Top 5 and rest",
             fill = "")
      
    } else {
      
      bundesland <- input$region

          coord_polar("y", start = 0) +
